<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="97a9bec1-a5fe-551b-82f0-56a00c61ac6f" activityNameId="29c7ee96-775e-415d-bf41-c34d90bf014e" parentActivityId="a6c62d33-e9f8-54ba-8259-d18c66e9c331" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">sodium sulfite production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">SODIUM SULFITE</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Sodium sulphite</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">7757-83-7</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Sodium sulfite anhydrous</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Sulftech sodium sulfuret</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Disodium sulfite</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of sodium sulfite, including materials, energy uses, infrastructure, and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of sodium sulfite from sulfur dioxide in Europe. Sodium sulfite (Na2SO3) is a white solid, which is predominantly marketed as the anhydrous salt. Sodium sulfite is used as a reducing agent, for the production of sodium thiosulfate, in the photography, paper, and textile industries, for treating boiler water, and as a food preservative. Sodium sulfite is sold in various purity grades containing 90 – 98 % Na2SO3. The salt can be stored for long periods if kept dry, with the exclusion of air. It is transported in plastic and paper sacks. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Sodium sulfite is produced by treating a suspension of sodium hydroxide or sodium carbonate with sulfur dioxide. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">NaOH + SO2 → Na2SO3 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The temperature is maintained at 60 – 80 °C for optimal crystal separation. The sodium sulfite suspension formed is centrifuged and the salt dried. Some sodium sulfite is obtained from the scrubbing of SO2-containing off-gases. Production processes using an anhydrous route have not yet achieved industrial importance.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, the raw materials are modelled with a stoechiometric calculation. The emissions are estimated, and the energy and water consumptions are approximated based on data from a large chemical factory (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Frischknecht R., Jungbluth N., Althaus H.-J., Doka G., Dones R., Heck T., Hellweg S., Hischier R., Nemecek T., Rebitzer G. and Spielmann M. (2007) Overview and Methodology. Final report ecoinvent v2.0 No. 1. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH, retrieved from: www.ecoinvent.org.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">José Jiménez Barberá, Adolf Metzger, Manfred Wolf: Sulfites, Thiosulfates, and Dithionites. Published online: 2003. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: DOI: 10.1002/14356007.a25_477</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe but is assumed to be representative of the global production. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Sodium sulfite is produced by treating a suspension of sodium hydroxide or sodium carbonate with sulfur dioxide. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">NaOH + SO2 → Na2SO3 + H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The temperature is maintained at 60 – 80 °C for optimal crystal separation. The sodium sulfite suspension formed is centrifuged and the salt dried. Some sodium sulfite is obtained from the scrubbing of SO2-containing off-gases. Production processes using an anhydrous route have not yet achieved industrial importance.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2010-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of publications. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
